org.wickedsource.logunit

Class Expectation

  • java.lang.Object
    • org.wickedsource.logunit.Expectation

  • public class Expectation
extends Object
    A LogUnit expectation defines what is expected to be logged during a unit test.

    Tom Hombergs

    • Constructor Detail

      • Expectation

        public Expectation(Pattern pattern)
        Constructs an expectation with a given regular expression pattern. The expectation will be fulfilled if a log message matching this pattern is logged.
        Parameters:
        pattern - the pattern that is expected to be logged.

      • Expectation

        public Expectation(Pattern pattern,
           LogLevel level)
        Constructs an expectation with a given regular expression pattern and a given log level. The expectation will be fulfilled if a log message matching the pattern with the given log level is logged.
        Parameters:
        pattern - the pattern that is expected to be logged.
        level - the log level that the message is expected to be logged on.

      • Expectation

        public Expectation(Pattern pattern,
           LogLevel level,
           String loggerName)
        Constructs an expectation with a given regular expression pattern, a given log level and a given logger name. The expectation will be fulfilled if a log message matching the given pattern is logged on the given log level and the logger with the given name.
        Parameters:
        pattern - the pattern that is expected to be logged.
        level - the log level that the message is expected to be logged on.
        loggerName - the name of the logger that is expected to log the message.

      • consumeLogEvent

        public void consumeLogEvent(LogUnitEvent event)
        Consumes a LogUnitEvent and compares the data in the event to the data expected by this Expectation. If the comparison is successful, this Expectations "fulfilled" status is updated.s
        Parameters:
        event - the log event that contains the data to compare to the expected data.
